# 4. Lambda Syntax

General syntax

```java
(parameters) -> expression
```

or

```java
(parameters) -> {

    statements

}
```

Think of it like this

```
Input

↓

Process

↓

Output
```

The arrow means

```
takes this

↓

does this
```

---

# Case 1 No Parameters

```java
() -> System.out.println("Hello")
```

Let's understand.

```
()

↓

No inputs

↓

->

↓

Execute this statement
```

Equivalent method

```java
void greet() {

    System.out.println("Hello");

}
```

---

# Case 2 One Parameter

```java
name -> System.out.println(name);
```

Equivalent

```java
void print(String name){

    System.out.println(name);

}
```

Notice

No datatype required.

Java already knows.

---

# How?

Suppose interface

```java
interface Printer{

    void print(String name);

}
```

Compiler already knows

```
print()

↓

takes String

↓

therefore

name is String
```

So we don't need

```java
(String name)
```

Although this is also correct.

---

# Case 3 Two Parameters

```java
(a,b) -> a+b
```

Equivalent

```java
int add(int a,int b){

    return a+b;

}
```

---

# Why no return?

Many beginners ask this.

Lambda

```java
(a,b)->a+b
```

looks incomplete.

Actually Java automatically adds

```java
return
```

So internally

```java
(a,b)->{

    return a+b;

}
```

---

# But if we write braces?

Then

```java
(a,b)->{

    return a+b;

}
```

Return becomes mandatory.

Wrong

```java
(a,b)->{

    a+b;

}
```

Compilation Error

---

# 5. Parameter Rules

## No parameter

```java
()->System.out.println("Hi");
```

---

## One parameter

No brackets needed

```java
x->x*x
```

Also valid

```java
(x)->x*x
```

Both correct.

---

## Two parameters

Brackets compulsory.

Correct

```java
(a,b)->a+b
```

Wrong

```java
a,b->a+b
```

